SIMPLE: slug
RECORDS: 5

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Slug
<hw>Slug</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>slugge</ets>
slothful, <ets>sluggen</ets> to be slothful; cf. LG. <ets>slukk</ets>
low-spirited, sad, E. <ets>slack</ets>, <ets>slouch</ets>, D.
<ets>slak</ets>, <ets>slek</ets>, a snail.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A
drone; a slow, lazy fellow; a sluggard.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A hindrance; an obstruction.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any one of numerous species of
terrestrial pulmonate mollusks belonging to Limax and several related
genera, in which the shell is either small and concealed in the mantle,
or altogether wanting. They are closely allied to the land
snails.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any smooth, soft larva of a
sawfly or moth which creeps like a mollusk; <as>as, the pear
<ex>slug</ex>; rose <ex>slug</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A ship that sails slowly.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Halliwell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His rendezvous for his fleet, and for all <qex>slugs</qex> to come
to, should be between Calais and Dover.</q>
<rj><qau>Pepys.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <ety>[Perhaps a different word.]</ety> <def>An
irregularly shaped piece of metal, used as a missile for a gun.</def><--
also, a colloq. term for bullet. -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Print.)</fld> <def>A thick strip of metal less than
type high, and as long as the width of a column or a page, -- used in
spacing out pages and to separate display lines, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Sea slug</b></col>. <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd>
<cd>Any nudibranch mollusk</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>A holothurian.</cd> --
<col><b>Slug caterpillar</b></col>. <cd>Same as
<er>Slugworm</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Slug</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Slug
<hw>Slug</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To move slowly; to lie idle.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>slug</qex> in sloth and sensual delight.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Slug</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Slug
<hw>Slug</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To make sluggish.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Slug</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Slug
<hw>Slug</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Slugged</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Slugging</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To load
with a slug or slugs; <as>as, to <ex>slug</ex> a gun</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To strike heavily.</def> <mark>[Cant or
Slang]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Slug</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Slug
<hw>Slug</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To become reduced in diameter, or
changed in shape, by passing from a larger to a smaller part of the bore
of the barrel; -- said of a bullet when fired from a gun, pistol, or
other firearm.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Slugabed</ent>⟦br⟧
